text:
are you thankful for what you have?  if we are always wanting more, but not thankful for what we currently have, we will not be thankful, appreciative, or deserving of more.

make it a daily practice to be thankful.  acknowledge what it is that you have to give thanks.  you will be surprised at how much more you receive when you recognize what you already have üíú

text:
the british deputy high commission @ukinindia is partnering with the indian institute of journalism & new media (iijnm) in a panel discussion addressing issues relevant to the indian context in tackling violence against girls and women (vawg) on december 5, 2018, from 1800hrs at the jw marriott hotel, vittal mallya road.

the panel discussion is being organized¬†keeping in mind the 16 days of activism against gender-based violence, an international campaign to challenge violence against women and girls (vawg). the campaign runs every year from 25 november, the international day for the elimination of violence against women, to 10 december, human rights day.

this year, the campaign takes special significance with the #metoo moment. the media play a crucial role in highlighting the prevalence of violence in society, especially gender-related violence.

the¬†panel¬†discussion will raise¬†the question of whether the media can turn the spotlight inwards and change the way it covers vawg.

speakers
ammu joseph
nisha susan
dakshina murthy
anubha bonsle
nupur basu

@regran_ed from @649royalty -  so the next question is, if they're not picking people based on talent what criteria are they using when pickling people for record deals? putting aside the fact that half of these male and female artists are probably victims of, or willing participants in the #metoo movement, the major record labels are owned by private prisons who have a vested interest in keeping people in jail. funnily enough, most artists pushed by the mainstream either encourage drug culture (making, selling and using drugs) or an anti family agenda. drugs can either kill you or land you in jail, and without a two parent household with a loving family helping keep you on the right track you are more likely to lose your way and wind up in jail - fattening the pockets of the people that own private prisons. according to most mainstream artists, men should forget about love, not worry about doing good in the world and focus only on money, fantasize over plastic bodies, buy women's loyalty with material things, not trust any women, break their hearts and have sex with as many as possible. according to the mainstream, women should never trust any men, play them every chance they get, be loyal only to themselves, not pursue any careers or goals and forget about finding a good man and starting a family. then people wonder why depression and anxiety rates are skyrocketing - if all the music you listen to tells you you need to be rich to be happy, you're not going to appreciate the fact that if you have a roof over your head and food in your stomach you're already doing better than half the world. watch what you consume, stop eating low hanging fruit - food is either medicine or poison, and music is food for the soul üëå - #regrann

text:
sometimes women learn the hard way of what it means to freeze in the face of danger. it's a learned habit, sometimes even when no danger is present. body language can speak a thousand words. there is a difference between consent and vacancy. never assume her silence is consent.
‚Äî b o d y  l a n g u a g e
¬© sarah doughty
.
think about this. if she's making eyes, it doesn't mean consent. if she's barely dressed, it doesn't mean consent. did it ever occur to you that asking if it's okay is not only sexy, but empowering? if she doesn't say yes, the answer is no.
.
.
you might be wondering why i'm sharing this now. you may wonder why anyone with a story of abuse or assault may wait decades before coming forward ‚Äî if they ever say anything at all. the answer is simple: any time is a good time. the issue is unfortunate. that there's not enough people talking about this and how important it is to not only know the difference, but to stop blaming the victims. start conversations. teach your children what's okay and what is not. just do something.
.
and right now, that's exactly what i'm doing. 'we will not be silenced' is an important anthology of poetry, prose, essays, and even art for everyone ‚Äî survivors, victims, help centers, and even law enforcement. and yes, you. find more information about this book and what you can do to help on my website.
.

‚Äúi defended myself and left. for a while i was left with the fear that it would have destroyed my career. all the actresses were afraid of him. i also left lars von trier's antichrist set before filming started because i had asked him about the sex scenes but he did not even want to talk about it with me. unpleasant moments have happened to me even with other directors and producers, but i dealt with it on my own and i did not talk about it publicly. then, a year ago, thanks to the other women who told their stories, all much more dramatic than mine, i added my name to the list. the scenario has changed and will change again. it takes a treatment, even economic, more respectful and fair for women, as cate blanchett said. write it: i want cate blanchett president of the universe.‚Äù
- eva green on her sexual harassment experience, the #metoo movement and the positive changes that it brings

text:
everyone responds to trauma in different ways. there are no "right or wrong ways." you just respond. 5 years ago my life changed forever when i became a survivor of sexual assault at the age of 34. on episode 3 a friend interviews me about my story.
‚ù§ 
for those who haven't experienced sexual trauma, i hope this will give you a better glimpse into what life is like for a survivor.
‚ù§ 
for those who are survivors, i hope my story will provide some comfort and encouragement. you are not alone. next monday, haven will open. haven is an online space with videos and an online community for survivors who identify as female. i'll post on monday once it opens.
‚ù§ 
on the website (link in bio), there are more resources for survivors of all genders and supporters of survivors. #restoringheart #emotionalhealth #mentalhealth #hope #survivor #metoo #icwlh #sexualassault #timesup #healing #podcast

from now until the campaign ends on 10 december i will be sharing the basic steps and information you need to have available when applying for a protection/harassment order. many people think that the abuse has to be physical in order for one of the mentioned orders to be granted which means that you may be a victim without appreciating just how serious the offending conduct by the other person is. i will try to make the posts as informative as possible and i will also ask friends of friends to give ancillary advice ie: medical and procedural (court) related advice. please do take part in the conversations because it is all our duty to help friends of sisters if they are victims of domestic violence. if your story is more personal and you feel you may need professional help please dm me and i will make sure to put you or a sister in contact with a professional.

text:
i was assaulted in a parking lot on december 4, 2015. 
i felt inside out, re-traumatized and remembering the feeling of losing my home, my body. my heart was too heavy in my chest. i welcomed shame & embarrassment like old friends, kept what happened a secret for months. i was afraid to be blamed, but the truth was i had already blamed myself. how could this have happened again? what had i done? my fault, my fault, my fault. 
it‚Äôs been three years and even though i remember the date, i no longer find it to be a sad story. instead, i have returned the shame. i have fought my way through sadness, through anger, through desperation. i have forgiven the person for what they did. 
and i survived. 
#endsexualviolence #yesallwomen #metoo #tellmydaughters #survivor #liveyourtruth ‚Ä¢

text: ever since i was a child, people have been expecting me to stay in my designated lane as a #blackfemale. and they're actually offended when i don't. there was a crisis at my primary school in 1988 when i managed to be the best performing student. eventually the prize i was supposed to win was divided between 10 students. i am not supposed to excel. i am not supposed to get a good job. to be well-read. i was not supposed to marry outside my race. or my class. i am not supposed to talk about race issues in the #netherlands (the subtext being, i should be grateful to have citizenship and only talk about pleasant things like tulips). why is it that we, as females, can tell our #metoo stories but not share our experiences on #race? #africa #race #southafrica #seadanourhussen #claricegargard @nrcnl @trouw.deverdieping
name: African Design Collective

text:
part one; the sponsor issue

i am a young girl

i just joined city campus

my dream is to graduate in good time

i have amazing classmates 
the say i have a hot body

but i want to believe i am just beautiful

older men have noticed that i have what my classmates say i have

this particular one is prominent,

he waits for me by the school gate

he keeps offering me money

but, hey, i am from the village and i need to look like a city girl too

i do truly have a hot body, i have realized it now

here in the city, it's a money maker

what do i do?

what will my classmates think if i accept the older man's offer?

what of my schooling?

will i be able to balance?

#hearmetoo #metoo #genderbasedaviolence

text:
rules for best friends
-
1. i don't care if you're busy, if i call you, you must pickup either to talk to me or tell me that you're busy.
-
2. if you keep anything secret and i do find it from someone else, i may kill you.
-
3. only i can make you cry
if someone else does, we'll team up to punch his/her face.
-
4. i'm always with you, remember that, but you still have to be independent.
-
5. my girlfriend/boyfriend will be jealous of you. but that doesn't mean you have to go. they have their place and you have yours.
-
6. i can see what's on your mind with just your texts. so don't try to act smart, you're not.
-
7. lying is strictly prohibited and can be punished by a punishment treat anytime i want and wherever i want. so think twice before lying.
-
8. i'll never respect you in private and will never disrespect you in public.
-
9. i don't care if i'm in a relationship, i'll still love you the way i do
-
10. evil plans will always be our collaboration.
-
11. if you're ill, you'll sleep early and eat when told and take regular medicines. your cuteness will not help you get away.
-
12. taunting is permitted till it is true.
-
13. nobody else can call you by your nickname except me or your family.
-
14. your family is my family.
-
15. if you want to cry, you can only cry when you're with me. you won't ever cry before anybody else.
-
16. remember and understand that nobody else can handle you except me. so even if you go, you'll be back in few days.
-
17. during fights, you can't switch off your phone or go offline anytime in between. a fight started will have to be finished in one sitting.
-
18. before getting into relationship, i need that girl/guy('s) name so that i can stalk and gain information whether he/she is right for you.
-
19. if i start singing a song, it's your duty to complete it.
-
20. i just need one promise, that you'll be there forever.
.
.
vaibhav thorat.
(@theumbrellastories)
.
.

text:
what a year 2018 has been! majority of which we‚Äôve spent in retrogrades (planets moving backwards), illuminating the past and showing us old patterns of thinking, behaviors and states of being that were ripe for change - the #metoo movement being the prime example. 
#metoo pulled a scab off, allowing us to see, own, address and begin to heal portions of our psyche that we may have buried and left behind. 
whether it was that moment or a different one, each of us has had the opportunity to witness, awaken and recalibrate our belief system and sense of self worth. 
i know for me, the suicides of kate spade and anthony bourdain, flipped a switch. a switch that both, surprised and compelled me forward. 
while our lives may not look the way we imagined they would eight or even four years ago, we have, in many ways, come full circle. 
2018 has served to catch us up to ourselves. we don‚Äôt have to hide who we are, our fallibility or our journey. 
the life we yearned for, though different than we had imagined, is here; that is something to embrace and celebrate! 
wednesday night (12/5), join @jaybrownnetwork @ludogabriele @dricheson @spencerjacobson_ , & @consciousness_architect, at 7:30 pm est on fb live to celebrate the leaps we‚Äôve made in this epically long year of shifts, turns, reviews and surprises...

part three: the sponsor issue

the truth is, we have been meeting severally

he fears for his reputation

i want security, the baby is my security, so i am keeping it

text:
i get it. i get why this is. wall street, as a whole, is an industry built by men for men. despite that, i have been blessed enough to have had male leaders and mentors that have only championed my gender and highlighted the ways i am different as strengths, not weaknesses, in the field of wealth management; who have celebrated my diversity and now my role as a mother as advantages and not setbacks to my success in the industry. now that wall street‚Äôs foundations are being shaken and reshaped, things like this are bound to happen. growing pains, so to speak. i‚Äôm certain that in time, this cycle of trial and error will result in a more synergistic working environment and professional experience for us all. #wallstreet #womeninwallstreet #metoomovement 
@regrann from @bloombergbusiness - wall street has adopted a new strategy in the #metoo era: avoid women altogether.

call it the pence effect, after u.s. vice president mike pence, who says he avoids dining alone with any women who aren't his wife.

in finance, the impact could essentially be gender segregation, and wall street risks becoming even more of a boy's club, rather than less of one. ‚Äúwomen are grasping for ideas on how to deal with it, because it is affecting our careers,‚Äù a senior vice president at wells fargo & co said. ‚Äúit‚Äôs a real loss.‚Äù

text:
simple pleasures and magnified gratitude
.
.
.
i've been thrilled to have these gorgeous flowers on my dining table this week, a takeaway from my coach @robertcarlnotter's neurocoaching workshop on saturday where i received so much more
.
.
.
these flowers have served as a coaching tool for enlightening my trauma patients this week - and currently represent the immense #gratitude i have for my coach who has equipped me with a renewed commitment to honing my niche in 2019.
.
.
.
after 43 years as an empath, 15 years in naturopathic practice, 12 years hypnotizing, 10 years in mental health and 6 months in regression therapy, i am rejuvenated - spreading my wings to support others in spreading theirs #spirituality
.
.
.

text:
the reveal. 
this is the first time i have made my artwork public.  i have always kept it close to my heart, i didn‚Äôt need people judging, their approval and i certainly didn‚Äôt know at the time how to explain the pieces i was/have been creating. 
this piece is a product of the #metoo movement. the colour represents envy of the image-mirage people create for society. the sometimes fake-happy or the ‚Äòi‚Äôm fine‚Äô response we portray on the outside to the outsiders. 
her right arm and left hand isn‚Äôt shaded the same to show how we appear strong but sometimes we, ourselves, don‚Äôt even realize how we can fall apart or that it is inevitable. #broken 
we are all vulnerable to something or someone at some point in our lives. we as society have a tendency to want to turn away from it but we will all be healthier if we just stop ignoring we are all human.

#womenartists #canadianartist #canadianart #vulnerability #humility #oilpastel #inthistogether #standstrong #novascotianartist #halifax #timeheals

photo: map of the trans-siberian railway journey‚†Ä
‚†Ä
the trans-siberian railway‚†Ä
no railway has captured the imagination like the trans-siberian. running almost 6000 miles long through some of the most inhospitable yet gripping landscapes on earth, it has seduced travelers and dreamers alike since its inception. traveling across eight time zones ‚Äì a third of the planet ‚Äì from great cities to rural fairytale villages, across the pristine wilderness of the ural mountains, through the immense russian steppe and the awe-inspiring lake baikal, the trans-siberian is the longest passenger rail trip in the world ‚Äì and one of the greatest possible travel experiences.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
read further at https://buff.ly/2bot3ks on the history of the trans-siberian railway that lily used to travel in russia, in the blog: the trans-siberian railway‚†Ä
‚†Ä

text:
i am really excited about the women‚Äôs movement taking over. i feel like things are possible for me now that ten years ago i would have never given a thought to. in the culture i grew up in, i felt like it was a boys club, and ‚Äòboys will be boys‚Äô was too quickly accepted. i still see that today to some extent, but it is slowly getting crushed, and that is what is making me excited. .

i have been date raped before, and i had no one to talk to about it. my close friends were date raped in high school as well. it was just something that was accepted and you felt as a girl that you had to do certain things to be accepted by people. .
.

women wouldn‚Äôt talk to each other about these things before. women were pinned against each other by men and were competitive with each other. now women are talking about their experiences in the #metoo movement and i feel like there is a sisterhood now. before we were enemies, and now we are sisters. .

i am not saying all men are like this, but i think overall men need to empathize with women, and treat a woman the way you would want someone to treat your mother or your sister. men and women are wired differently, and women feel like they can‚Äôt even be friends with men, because men seem to only think sexually. i wish men would see women as a human being to be respected, and not just as a person to try and have sex with.
.

women need to realize they don‚Äôt need anybody to make them happy. a person should add to your happiness, not be the source of your happiness.‚Äù ~ ocean county mall 
#strongwomen

text:
@arimelber @donlemoncnn @seanhannity @maddowshow @thejimmydoreshow @cnn @nbcnews wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
@arimelber @donlemoncnn @seanhannity @maddowshow @thejimmydoreshow @cnn @nbcnews wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
i love watching the movie ‚Äúlove actually‚Äù! i enjoy indulging myself in watching it - and this is the time of the year for it!  when i curled up under my comfy blanket and flipped on the tv over the weekend, the movie was just beginning - perfect timing!

this scene caught my eye on how true it is - especially when we‚Äôre working to make a change. 
when we decide to change, we think about the positive impact these changes will make on our life.  while we are being positive and goal focused, others are thinking about the impact on them.  if we are setting boundaries and enforcing them, those who like to push our limits will not be all that pleased.  if we are taking time to care for us and requiring others to manage differently, they won‚Äôt necessarily be happy about our new self-care plan.  if we are starting our own business, we might be told how risky it is and not to come crying when it fails.

we are often left shocked and surprised that everyone is not on board with us improving our lives.  they are wondering how their lives will change because of us.  remember, these changes are for us and to improve our lives.  we cannot be pleasing everyone and if that is our focus, we will never be happy!  keep taking care of you üíú

text:
@arimelber @donlemoncnn @seanhannity @maddowshow @thejimmydoreshow @cnn @nbcnews wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
i had dinner with one of my friends last week‚Äîshe‚Äôs a therapist, and her insights are always so helpful. we were smiling and near happy tears as we reflected how far we had both come. two and a half years ago, we were both filled with fear. fear because we both found ourselves reeling after ending our abusive relationships. we were lost and afraid. .
.
‚Äúthank god for post-traumatic growth,‚Äù she said. i had no idea what she was talking about. as she explained, i felt a sense of pride. she was right, i had really grown from the trauma. here‚Äôs what the apa says about ptg:
. "resiliency is the personal attribute or ability to bounce back," says taku. ptg, on the other hand, refers to what can happen when someone who has difficulty bouncing back experiences a traumatic event that challenges his or her core beliefs, endures psychological struggle (even a mental illness such as post-traumatic stress disorder), and then ultimately finds a sense of personal growth. it's a process that "takes a lot of time, energy and struggle," taku says.
someone who is already resilient when trauma occurs won't experience ptg because a resilient person isn't rocked to the core by an event and doesn't have to seek a new belief system, explains tedeschi. less resilient people, on the other hand, may go through distress and confusion as they try to understand why this terrible thing happened to them and what it means for their world view. #weareher #posttraumaticgrowth #ptsd #heal #empower #restore #narcissisticabuse #youareenough #believesurvivors #survivor #empoweringwomen #metoo #nomore #mentalhealth #growth

text:
3.5 years later and i‚Äôm still fighting: 
with the help of my dearest friend in the entire world, i finally found a sort of closure i have been longing for nearly two years. together we went out into the woods of my upbringing, armed with a camera and three articles of clothing; the panties i wore the early morning of august 17th 2015, the dress i was raped in, and my attacker‚Äôs hat. for nearly two years i kept these items, not knowing what to do with them. the journey to self-affirmation is an everyday struggle but am so grateful to have a beautiful soul like cole mcdonnell  there to document this immensely cathartic experience. a kind of baptism by fire.  i do not want to be pitied for my experience. it is mine and mine alone‚Ä¶ it shaped me into the being i am today. it forced me admit things about myself that i was too blinded to see for many years. for so long i played to victim, turning streams into rampant rivers‚Ä¶ always finding a reason to blame anyone but myself for my misery and flaws. it wasn‚Äôt until i became the victim where i realized how much i didn‚Äôt want to be one.

text:
after my rape: 
the people who i thought would be there, fell by the wayside. a 13-year relationship with my ‚Äúbest friend‚Äù, the girl who i had always imagined being my future maid of honor, was severed. a seven-year relationship with a man who was going to be the godfather to my future children was broken. the pain of telling my father, mother, sister, and boyfriend was incredible. the loss of my friends at times pushed me to my mental brink. the triggers and flash backs still haunt me till this very day. but i am still here‚Ä¶ i am still fighting, and i never intend on stopping.  my true family and friends will never understand the impact they have had on me, particularly over the last two years. they helped me push through my darkest days and the dark moments still to come. the most important thing this experience  exposed was my inner strength to preserver; an inner strength so primal and solid, it leaves little room for my previously crippling self-doubt. i endured my biggest fear and determined to not let it define me. i don‚Äôt want pity, i just want to be that voice for those too scared to speak.

text:
stop telling women to smile.
a series with a powerful and simply intricate message, by tatyana fazlalizadeh (@tlynnfaz) . . . . . .
people don‚Äôt always hear what you tell them.
men look, but won‚Äôt listen.
art is a strong way to get a message across.
tatyana has an ongoing series where she created portraits of women and included a small but commonly shared experience regarding street harassment, cat calling, and other forms of jaded sexism and violations against women in public. 
i wanted to mention a few stories from her work, but i want you to check it out yourself because there‚Äôs a lot of bad ass goodness that‚Äôs should be spread around! @stoptellingwomentosmile ...there‚Äôs some pretty obvious issues and statement that are addressed in her series.
the facts that we aren‚Äôt here to be a sensual ray of sunshine when we walk out is a given.
i do want to mention (since it‚Äôs not obvious to some people) that women are not rude, over sensitive, overreacting, or aggressive when ignoring or rejecting  a ‚Äúpolite hello‚Äù.
there are gestures, tone, twitches, looks, etc., that differentiates a polite ‚Äúhello‚Äù from a hello that will lead to ‚Äúalright now lemme holla atchu‚Äù. people, specifically men, can be very privileged in being oblivious to noticing this‚Äî considering the lack of experience they have in regards to unapologetic harassment. 
so if you see a women who is stand-offish in public, giving men the death stare as she walks by. don‚Äôt call her rude, ....because she has had enough.
along with her sisters, mothers, grandmothers, and ancestors.
and asking for, or suggesting a little smile, is just the chauvinistic cherry on top of a depleted, bloody, and raw cake. . . . . . . . .
i saw tatyana and her art in oakland almost five years ago, and it inspired me to dive more into creating my own portraits, as well as being more vocal about catcalling and harassment.
so this is a pure appreciation post for @tlynnfaz, women, art, and honestly myself.

text:
bet's miniseries is a cheaply made (though endlessly watchable) attempt to redeem singer bobby brown from public villainy. 
a man lays on the floor next to broken glass, collapsed from a drug overdose. truthfully, it's a bit shocking to see whitney houston (gabrielle dennis, vivacious) portrayed as a coke-. but , ex-husband and singer bobby brown is now clearly asking, "what about bobby? unfortunately comes off as a different kind of #metoo story ‚Äî one that poses, "what if abusers were the true victims all along? , the bobby brown story is sequel-ish to the point that the bobby brown story is a typical musician biopic, showcasing the rise, fall, and redemption of a scoundrel.) scanning from the 1980s through today, we see brown (woody mcclain) morph from persona to persona: nasally teen heartthrob, bad-boy solo artist, wanton womanizer, paranoiac drug fiend, absentee father, doting father, grieving father. to counter the laughably apocryphal scenes of brown boinking everyone from janet jackson (played by cree davis) to three women at once on his tour bus ("hurry this shit up, man" says his brother, whom i fully agree with), he's eventually saved by a good woman. brown's various relationships are underdeveloped, and the always-welcome mekhi phifer is wasted in a small role as his brother and former manager, tommy. mcclain humanizes brown, who, throughout the mini, frequently refers to the pain of colorism in an industry that values light skin. "'america's little princess. 'why is she with that thug? he's too ghetto for her, he's too ugly for her. he's a leach¬† it's true brown has been vilified in the press as hades enticing young persephone into the underworld, and you may appreciate seeing a different side of the story. you may very nearly buy it, too. i believe the real-life brown loves his children, and that witnessing his former love and daughter die tragically and similarly within three years of one another has been heartbreaking for him.¬† concert sequences reveling in brown's fervent bops and mcclain's enviable dancing skills. here, you finally get a sense of brown's talent and allure, and what made him a sex symbol that's my prerogative.

text:
‚ñ™what does it mean?: self-care‚ñ™
self-care is such an important - although challenging - aspect of healing and recovery. it's also something for everyone to practice -- to look after themselves, prevent burn out, stand confident in their worth, and restore their resources.
.
for complex trauma survivors, self-care can actually feel threatening, scary, shameful, undeserved, or rife with guilt. if you've been taught that you only deserve pain or that any time spent on yourself is self-centered, indulgent, or even a waste of time, it can be really difficult to break through those messages and try to slowly introduce self-respecting, self-loving acts into one's life. yet, it is so very important and imperative to one's physical and mental health.
.
self-care has received more attention in recent years, which is awesome! but, it extends beyond what one can accomplish on a sunday. speaking kindly to yourself, setting boundaries, maintaining therapy appointments, moving from a toxic neighborhood, and so much more can all be acts of self-care. you deserve to look after yourself, meet your needs, do what is best for mental and physical wellbeing. we know that is hard. it takes strength to do what is best for you. you can do this.
.
üíúüíôüíõ
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
trigger warning 
excerpt from #metoo: a collection of true story crimes against women‚Äù
‚Äúas this man walked me to my car, he began grabbing my butt. though we had kissed, i was not comfortable with him touching me in this way. i playfully told him to stop. nevertheless, i allowed him to continue walking me to my car. as we arrived at my car, i turned to face him. i was simply going to thank him for walking me to my car. he then pushed me against the car door and began kissing me fiercely. i put my hand on his chest, pushed him away, and told him i was done for the night and would be leaving now. he then became angry...‚Äù
.
.
my latest project is called ‚Äú#metoo: a collection of true story crimes against women.‚Äù
i am still collecting stories and poems.
submissions will be accepted until december 31, 2018.
if you have a story/poem that you would like to include email me at mchillstromauthor@yahoo.com.
all stories/poems will be listed as anonymous submissions.
the types of stories i am looking for include personal experiences of:
-sexual harassment -rape/assault -sexual, emotional, or physical abuse
-stalking
-gender discrimination
-i will accept other topics if they fit in with the theme as well.
through writing about my own experiences i have found peace and strength.
i hope others will find this as well and that the future readers of this collection will find courage and strength in the knowledge that they are not alone.
proceeds from the sales of this collection will be donated to help sexual assault survivors.
name: Michelle C. Hillstrom - Author

.
.

all stories/poems will be listed as anonymous submissions.

text:
by¬†julie k. brownnov. 28, 2018

palm beach county courthouse

june 30, 2008

jeffrey edward epstein appeared at his sentencing dressed comfortably in a blue blazer, blue shirt, jeans and gray sneakers. his attorney, jack goldberger, was at his side.

at the end of the 68-minute hearing, the 55-year-old silver-haired financier ‚Äî accused of sexually abusing dozens of underage girls ‚Äî was fingerprinted and handcuffed, just like any other criminal sentenced in florida.

but inmate no. w35755 would not be treated like other convicted sex offenders in the state of florida, which has some of the strictest sex offender laws in the nation.

ten years before the #metoo movement raised awareness about the kid-glove handling of powerful men accused of sexual abuse,¬†epstein‚Äôs lenient sentence and his extraordinary treatment¬†while in custody are still the source of consternation for the victims he was accused of molesting when they were minors.

beginning as far back as 2001,¬†epstein lured a steady stream of underage girls to his palm beach mansion¬†to engage in nude massages, masturbation, oral sex and intercourse, court and police records show. the girls ‚Äî mostly from disadvantaged, troubled families ‚Äî were recruited from middle and high schools around palm beach county. epstein would pay the girls for massages and offer them further money to bring him new girls every time he was at his home in palm beach, according to police reports.

the girls, now in their late 20s and early 30s, allege in a series of federal civil lawsuits filed over the past decade that epstein sexually abused hundreds of girls, not only in palm beach, but at his homes in manhattan, new mexico and in the caribbean.

in 2007, the fbi had prepared a 53-page federal indictment charging epstein with sex crimes that could have put him in federal prison for life. but then-miami u.s. attorney¬†alexander acosta signed off on a non-prosecution agreement, which was negotiated, signed and sealed so that no one would know the full scope of of epstein‚Äôs crimes. the indictment was shelved, never to be seen again.

text: see what people are saying about candy apple butterscotch, #newauthor rebecca macceile‚Äôs debut publication. ‚Äúthis is an impactful read if you have ever experienced any sort of abuse. i appreciate the author‚Äôs candor and willingness to write with such openness. she takes responsibility for herself as much as she describes the lasting effects of trauma.‚Äù ‚Äúit is worth the read. it‚Äôs about a woman empowered and, my god, that is a wonderful thing indeed.‚Äù ‚Äúthe author gets to the point while still painting a very clear and definite picture for the readers and i love that. the accounts of the trauma are laid out in such a way that you know what‚Äôs happening and are able to imagine it but you aren‚Äôt bombarded with intense graphic imagery, which i appreciate as a survivor myself. would definitely recommend!‚Äù ‚Äúthis amazingly written gem takes you inside the author‚Äôs world and keeps you there, making you feel like a discreet ‚Äúbug on the wall.‚Äù i could not put it down.‚Äù ‚Äúi wish everyone would write a memoir. it would be so much easier to understand people. i haven‚Äôt been through anything as violent or traumatic, but i think this story is relatable in a lot of ways. it just makes me see a lot of things differently in every day life. it‚Äôs a big eye opener.‚Äù #onsalenow at the #linkinbio. #kindle and #paperback versions available! also for members of #amazonprime, candy apple butterscotch is available in the #kindlelendinglibrary as well as through #kindleunlimitedbooks! that‚Äôs right you can read for #free. #nonfictionbooks #memoir #metoo #ptsdsurvivor #kindlestoryteller2018  #kindledirectpublishing #onsalenow #paperback #kindlelendinglibrary #bookrecommendations #indieauthor #authorsofinstagram #amazon #readforfreekll

text:
i never thought i‚Äôd be brave enough to share this part of my life. though this is painful to share, i know we are stronger when we talk about our struggles-and i hope you will share yours with me below. (#metoo)
‚†Ä
when i was 21 i was slipped a date-rape drug.
the remaining details are not significant to my story, but something was taken from me that night that i‚Äôll never get back.
‚†Ä
the final words i was left with were ‚Äúi only gave you what you deserved‚Äù...which were words that pierced my heart and mind for many years to come.
‚†Ä
what i...deserved???
‚†Ä
i immediately turned to food for comfort. honestly, the more weight i gained-the safer i felt. i felt like if i was overweight, no one would find me attractive and i wouldn‚Äôt ever get hurt again.
‚†Ä
but the weight that i carried pierced much deeper.
‚†Ä
instead of dealing with it, i tucked it away in my mind and hoped i would never have to face it. i started eating my feelings instead...
‚†Ä
the sad reality is: 1 in 6 women will be a victim of sexual assault/rape. and it‚Äôs something we don‚Äôt talk about. at least i didn‚Äôt for many years. it was a secret i hid from the world because i felt so ashamed.
nobody is deserving of that. nobody. and it took me many years to fully believe that.
‚†Ä
i didn‚Äôt take care of myself anymore...
i didn‚Äôt love myself anymore...
food was the only comfort that i had...
the thought of taking it away made me uncomforable.
‚†Ä
but i took my life back...and so can you. i share this with you, because i know i‚Äôm not alone. many of us had an event that triggered us to gain weight. but the beautiful thing is: you have the power within you to overcome it.
.

americans are hella sleep. i tell my friends all the time about prepping cuz the economy is already sinking. we are at the latter end of the ponzi scheme.

this is the point where the ponzi scheme creater knows he is going to jail, so he tries to pimp some more money out of people. that's exactly what the huge powerball was about. they pimped y'all on lottery tickets, they pimped y'all on the highest online black friday year ever and they gonna pimp y'all asses on christmas too. when the collapse happens its gonna be super ugly for 80% of americans. y'all folks better stop spending on these holidays and prep while you can.

i realized when i took my road trip through the southern states america was fucked. the same applies to the north and midwest, those small cities are depleted.

being in a major city you may think every city is doing as good as yours is, but major cities are like 20% of america. when you go through these small towns in different states, many people are in bad shape. no jobs, no homes, homelessness, poverty, drugs and crime.

the small cities feel the pain years before it reaches the big cities. don't be fooled america is in trouble. there will come a time when people are throwing money in the streets and most people won't see it coming until that day hits.

free! (@freepublicart) an alternative, non-commercial contemporary art fair poised to be a historic convergence of some of the world‚Äôs most recognized and pioneering artists, will take place at @brickellcitycentre (701 south miami ave., miami, fl 33131) from december 6-9, 11am - 7pm.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
free! will present an intersectional group of over 50 artists; creating site-specific interventions in a non-traditional venue, curated by @anthony_spinello.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
free! is a convergence, a message, a uniquely immersive experience. now is a time for reflection, connectivity, and for healing - of the environment, our bodies, our nation, and our communities.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
free! interrupts and activates public spaces throughout the shopping center based on three core principles: free! public, free! play, and free! view. each sector addresses notions of healing, empathy and connectivity; to inspire, reflect and encourage participation from the public.

free! is generously supported by swire properties inc., in partnership with the john s. and james l. knight foundation.

yesterday, i wore a shirt that read ‚Äúi am a woman‚Äù and the interactions that occurred as a result made me reflect upon myself. what seemed like a simple quote turned into a complicated question: ‚Äúam i a woman?‚Äù ‚Å£
‚Å£
üå±‚Å£
‚Å£
the immediate observations made during this self-reflection revolved around being gracious, faithful, loving, patient, kind, nurturing, sweet, you know, the traditional ‚Äúfeminine‚Äù qualities. but i found was that a woman is so much more than the definition forced upon her. so much more profound than the expectations required of her. ‚Å£
‚Å£
üå± ‚Å£
‚Å£
turns out that a woman is one who can afford herself. one whose emotional, psychological, spiritual and physical maturity allow her to own herself. one who doesn‚Äôt need to lease or rent herself to others to make ends meet. turns out a woman is her own possession. not a slave of anyone else‚Äôs definition.‚Å£
‚Å£

text: astrophysicist and science educator neil degrasse tyson has been accused of sexual misconduct by three women. he denies the allegations. last month, patheos, a religion website, published the claims of three women who said tyson had inappropriately touched or harassed them. tyson disputed the allegations in a facebook post on sunday, saying, 'i see myself as loving husband and as a public servant ‚Äî a scientist and educator who serves at the will of the public.' via @nowthisnews #metoo

so israel just held a nationwide strike and it was an unreal display of activism.  tens of thousands of people protested throughout israel calling to end violence against women.
women of all backgrounds protested jerusalem >> haifa, i believe (photo cred unknown!) >> jerusalem >> tel aviv 
300 institutions (municipalies, corporations, and of course the non-profits) supported the strike, and allowed workers to take off work and join the day of protests (with pay). bridges and highways were blocked from the north to the south, and even the airport workers joined the strike for 40 minutes! 24 women have been murdered this year in israel. the protest calls for the government to release funding that was never actually allocated to programs that fight violence against women. #hearmeroar  #◊ê◊†◊ô◊ê◊ô◊©◊î◊ê◊†◊ô◊©◊ï◊ë◊™◊™ #strike #equality #violenceagainstwomen  #◊©◊ë◊ô◊™◊î #feminism #metoo #imwithher #protest #activism  #speakout

text: [cw: rape, police violence] i was privileged to have met @ashopcalledsara in group therapy provided by a local rape crisis center. we (and our amazing fellow members + therapists) created a support system through the peak of the #metoo movement while also processing our own traumas. today sara shares her story about the detective assigned to her rape case, neil kimball, a veteran of the los angeles sheriff‚Äôs department and a seasoned sex-crimes investigator. kimball was recently charged with raping a 14-year-old girl whose case he was investigating in the sex crimes bureau. he is also charged with dissuading the witness by intimidating this child from reporting the crime. this is not the only complaint made against him in his tenure on the sex crimes unit. when we say #believesurvivors, we‚Äôre not just talking about the specific case we are dealing with at the time. we‚Äôre talking about the way our law enforcement, judicial system, loved ones, colleagues, teachers, friends, whoever, respond to our reports. as @taranajaneen says, #metoo is a movement, not a moment. sara, thank you for bearing this burden that should not be yours. i am so, so proud of you. everyone: please read and share this story, it is so important for the safety of our community. and please fight harder so that the burden of ending sexual violence does not rely on the work of survivors. link in bio.

text:
dulu, sekitar 10 tahun yg lalu saat dimana anak-anak sedang senang-senangnya bermain,bercanda,tertawa. disaat itu saya kehilangan kehormatan saya.

dia, paman saya yg mengambil semuanya tanpa menyisakan sedikitpun. saat itu semua berjalan baik-baik saja, dengan imbalan mainan dan manisan dia mengajak saya kesebuah ruangan, dan semua terjadi disitu.

saat itu saya tidak mengerti, semua yg dia  lalukan saya tidak mengerti, sampai akhirnya sekarang saya sadari kehormatan saya telah dinodai, tidak suci lagi.

putus asa? ya , sempat terlintas dihati saya, mengakhiri hidup adalah pilihan yg paling tepat karna siapa yang mau menerima seseorang yg telah ternodai? apakah ada?. hanya menangis dalam diam, menangisi apa yg terjadi, dan menyalahkan diri sendiri.

apa yg harus saya lakukan?
-unknown

#hearmetoo #violenceagainstwomen #metoo #stoptheviolence #harassment #broken

text:
i'm learning, slowly, that it is not my job or responsibility to fix other people's toxic behavior. i grew up in a situation where i felt it was on me to always justify and excuse controlling, manipulative behavior. i had to hide my hurt and anger out of fear...fear of what someone would do, fear of the suicide threats, and i grew up feeling like it was my job to rescue or fix. to this day i have co-dependency issues. but i'm also learning that it's ok to say no. i don't have to justify or qualify my no. and if someone can't respect my attempt to set a boundary for myself (which can be a challenge), it's okay to stand up for myself. i'm not being "mean", it doesn't make me a bad person and asserting myself doesn't mean i'm being aggressive or that i don't care about the other person. 
#cptsd #ptsd #bpd #trauma #traumasurvivor #abuse #survivor #boundaries #selfcare #nomeansno #metoo #mentalhealth #mentalillness #mentalhealthawareness #breakthestigma #bpdstruggles #ptsdsurvivor

text:
this popped up in my newsfeed from last year at this time!  i was thinking about my new years resolutions because new years is just 4 weeks away!?! where did the time go?

so how did you do with those resolutions you made last year?  i know i had big plans to declutter, stress less and the old standby exercise more and clean up my diet.  well i hit about 50% of my target.  what about you? what was your excuse?  no time? don‚Äôt know what to eat?  no willpower?  i can help you combat every excuse you have to get your diet cleaned up and get moving. 
this year, i am getting systems in place to finally stick with those resolutions.  do you want to feel more energetic, joyful and mindful through the holidays?  yep #metoo

do you want to focus on self care instead of the usual self sabotage this holiday season?  yep #metoo

i personally know that the holidays are a time where it can be easy to spiral out of control with nutrition and fitness, especially with all the holiday events.  i am hosting an accountability group so we can finish 2018 strong! we are going to practice the 80 / 20 rule, give you helpful tips to keep your exercise and nutrition in check but still enjoy all the things you love about the holiday season. 
think about it...if you lost 1-2 pounds per week from now until new years...that translates to be 4-8 pounds lighter!  i can help you be successful this time for your new years resolutions!  we should chat!
.
.
.
.
.

text:
the one year anniversary of my rape was this weekend. i am am trying so hard to acknowledge how far i have come, but i can't help but feel broken. i don't even know what healing is or looks like at this point. 
and truthfully, i'm angry. i am about to graduate with my bachelor's degree, i have a future full of goals, i should be happy right now. i would be happy right now - if it weren't for him. and i hate that this has so much power over my life. i hate that i can't go a day, fuck it, even an hour, without thinking about it, picturing it, smelling it, and flashing to it in my mind. i hate feeling like i don't have control over my own thoughts. your thoughts and your body are just about the only things you truly own. and i still feel like they have been taken.
so i want you all to know, even as i am trying to help others, be inspiring, move forward in my life, i am still broken too. i realize, even on a page like this, these posts are a highlight reel of my healing (depressing, i know). it's not all "empowered survivor." sometimes i feel broken, and that is a reality i know so many of you understand. so today i am allowing myself to be broken. i'm allowing myself to eat cereal, go to bed at 9 p.m., and forget this day. today is a lost day. 
leave a üíô in the comments if you read this far.

text:
@regran_ed from @illuminatikillersofficial -  it all began at the tower of babel about 2,200 years before the birth our messiah in bethlehem.

nimrod (the grandson of noah) started a cult with his mother/wife semiramis where they offered up babies in a ‚Äúchild-mass‚Äù on altars to molech aka satan each year at the ‚Äúwinter solstice.‚Äù for twelve days leading up to december 25th, hundreds of child-sacrifices were conducted on the altar to this pagan deity. 
for each of the twelve months in the coming new year, there were twelve days of blood sacrifices that were meant to give the sun-god the ‚Äúlife-force‚Äù from these innocent children. 
and then by december 25th, they declared that the sun-god had come back to life. they called it the ‚Äúrebirth of the sun.‚Äù when nimrod was later executed for his crimes against children, his wife/mother became pregnant, and she concocted a story in order to keep this pagan religion alive in babylon. she told them that nimrod had impregnated her by the rays of the sun on march 25th (the vernal equinox, easter sun-day). exactly nine months later, on december 25th, semiramis gave birth to another son and she named him tammuz. 
semiramis then told the babylonians that nimrod had been reincarnated (reborn) on december 25th through her new-born son tammuz and that he was the god of the sun and she was the goddess of the moon. 
she then continued to practice child-sacrifices on the vernal equinox in remembrance of when she first conceived tammuz, and she taught the babylonians to dye eggs in the blood of these infants! semiramis was also renamed ishtar (easter) in other cultures because according to mythology, she rises (resurrects) in the ‚Äúeast‚Äù every spring on the vernal equinox from the underworld. this is why the pagans continue to sacrifice infants to her on ‚Äúeaster sun-day!‚Äù it is because the sun rises in the east and she is married to the sun-god!
@eddie.ik

text:
komnas perempuan mencatat setiap dua jam, ada 3 perempuan indonesia yang mengalami kekerasan.

terhitung sejak 2014, komnas perempuan sendiri telah menyatakan indonesia darurat kekerasan seksual. 
mengapa situasi ini disebut darurat? 
berdasarkan datanya:
pada 2014 ada 4.475 kasus kekerasan seksual yang menimpa perempuan dan anak perempuan.

angka tersebut meningkat pada 2015 menjadi 6.499 kasus dan di 2016 menjadi 5.785 kasus

desakan untuk mengesahkan ruu pks sesungguhnya telah lama disuarakan namun masih mandeg di dpr ri

padahal, indonesia mendapatkan rekomendasi dari komite konvensi penghapusan segala bentuk diskriminasi terhadap perempuan (cedaw) perserikatan bangsa-bangsa untuk membuat peraturan perundang-undangan yang menghapus kekerasan berbasis gender.

yuks, terus dorong dan desak pemerintah indonesia agar rancangan undang-undang penghapusan kekerasan seksual (ruu pks) segera disahkan!

cc: @alissa_wahid

#gerakbersama #pawai8des #sahkanruupks #16haktp #metoo #hearmetoo #buildingpeacewithindiversityfaitandsexual

komnas perempuan mencatat kasus kasus ini jumlahnya semakin meningkat tiap tahunnya. .
forum pengada layanan juga mencatat korban melapor datang setiap hari. .
karena itu, butuh solidaritas kita bersama, gerak kita bersama untuk menuntaskan masalah ini. 
ayo dorong dpr untuk segera membahas dan mengesahkan ruu penghapusan kekerasan seksual. karena bila tidak, saya, kamu, kita semua, dan orang yang kita sayangi bisa menjadi korban.

text:
you never know what people are going through. on the outside everything may look perfect but most of the time it‚Äôs not. and too often, some experience assault and abuse. whether it‚Äôs happening in their home or if they are personally affected, the emotional and mental toll that takes place is unbearable. for this young woman, her story was just that.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i started our stories matter so victims of assault, abuse, and domestic violence can be heard. having been a victim, i felt it was important to do something to make change. and this project means so much to me. i also teamed up with licensed psychotherapist @cosmicchristine to help provide a safe place for people to come forward and open up. i am grateful for her support as well as her dedication to the cause.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
we are currently accepting submissions for the project. sharing your story not only can be therapeutic, but can help others with healing and break through the ignorance we see on the issue. and you can be anonymous if it makes you more comfortable. this collaborative journal will be real, raw, eye-opening, heartbreaking, and inspirational.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i am honored to read your story and include it in this special series of bravery and strength. you can learn more at ourstoriesmatter.info
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

text:
#metoo is a relativly new movement that has taken over the whole world, and with good reason. a movement standing for victims of assult, sounds like something most people could get behind. but, i feel since everyone has been so silent about assult in the past, people forget that it's always been this way. villainizing the person standing up for something, ridiculing them and bringing them down until they're quiet. because of #metoo, women and men have been able to come foward with more support then ever.

this movie is called north country, this movie is based off the women workers at eveleth mines in minnesota, these women were the first to file a first class-action sexual harassment lawsuit. the movie is based on true heart turning events, but i believe it is the epitome of what #metoo stands for.

in the photo we have the main charater of the movie, josey, as she watches the anita hill testimony unfold. seeing as we just had a huge hearing happen in the us, ford hearing, i can find a say to connect the two of them. during the hearing for dr. christine blasey ford, many people compared her to anita hill, just one woman standing up against the top dogs. 
#northcountry #metoo #anitahill #ibelievechristineblaseyford

text:
kampanye 16 hari anti kekerasan terhadap perempuan (16 days of activism against gender violence) merupakan kampanye internasional untuk mendorong upaya-upaya penghapusan kekerasan terhadap perempuan di seluruh dunia. sebagai institusi nasional hak asasi manusia di indonesia, komnas perempuan menjadi inisiator kegiatan ini di indonesia. aktivitas ini sendiri pertama kali digagas oleh women‚Äôs global leadership institute tahun 1991 yang disponsori oleh center for women‚Äôs global leadership. setiap tahunnya, kegiatan ini berlangsung dari tanggal 25 november yang merupakan hari internasional penghapusan kekerasan terhadap perempuan hingga tanggal 10 desember yang merupakan hari hak asasi manusia (ham) internasional. dipilihnya rentang waktu tersebut adalah dalam rangka menghubungkan secara simbolik antara kekerasan terhadap perempuan dan ham, serta menekankan bahwa kekerasan terhadap perempuan merupakan salah satu bentuk pelanggaran ham. keterlibatan komnas perempuan dalam kampanye 16 hari anti kekerasan terhadap perempuan (haktp) telah dimulai sejak tahun 2003. dalam kampanye 16 haktp ini, komnas perempuan selain menjadi inisiator juga sebagai fasilitator pelaksanaan kampanye di wilayah-wilayah yang menjadi mitra komnas perempuan. hal ini sejalan dengan prinsip kerja dan mandat komnas perempuan yakni untuk bermitra dengan pihak masyarakat serta berperan memfasilitasi upaya terkait pencegahan dan penghapusan kekerasan terhadap perempuan.
#gerakbersama #pawai8des #sahkanruupks #16haktp #metoo #hearmetoo #kohatipb #kohatipbhmi #kohatiindonesia #kohaticerdas #kohatihmi #kohatimenginspirasi #kohatihits #kohatitangguh #kohatiku #kohatimillennial #kohatimilenial #kohatinusantara #kohatihebat #kohaticirebon

i staed our stories matter so victims of assault, abuse, and domestic violence can be heard. having been a victim, i felt it was impoant to do something to make change. and this project means so much to me. i also teamed up with licensed psychotherapist  to help provide a safe place for people to come forward and open up. i am grateful for her suppo as well as her dedication to the cause.

text:
trauma healing 101:  felt sense...awareness of how your body feels ‚Äúinside‚Äù‚Ä¶..your throat, heart, stomach, chest, circulation, etc.  it is your internal responses and body experiences. it is the combination of sensations + emotions. to help you start your ‚Äúfocus‚Äù on the felt sense you can start by closing your eyes for 1-3 minutes, then 1) sense your skin and notice the way your clothes feel, 2) sense underneath your skin, 3) how do you know you feel comfortable, 4) does becoming more aware of these sensations make you feel more or less comfortable? 5) does this change? 6)sit for a moment and enjoy the felt sense of feeling ‚Äúcomfortable‚Äù (from #wakingthetiger by #peter levine) üé®art via: @iambluegoddessinfinite ******************************

so it's that time of year again where parents tend to put together small gifts for their children's teachers as a little thank you for the year and a merry christmas. many like to stick to the simple option of chocolates or biscuits which is fair enough it's easy, and doesn't cost a lot, but i like to make something a little more personal and find ways of making cost effective gifts for my daughters support team, as she has quite a few she works with and they all do an incredible job. this year i made my own adaptation of a recipe for bath bombs and it actually turned out really awesome and every thing that went into everyone's parcels right down to the little unicorn charm on top each one came to a cost of $5.70 each. that to me is pretty decent when you look at the cost of a box of chocolates or biscuits can be nearly $10 or more, and not only were these were pretty easy to make, they smell amazing and i'm pretty sure will be much appreciated after a stressful year. ü§∏‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èü¶Ñüåà‚ù§Ô∏èüß°üíõüíöüíôüíúüéÖüéÑüòçüõÅüßò‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüå∫

3. satu akun hanya boleh berpartisipasi 1 kali
5. periode quiz 5-10 desember ¬†2018
6. samsara akan mengumumkan dan menghubungi pemenang pada tanggal 10 desember 2018

keputusan pemenang quiz adalah mutlak dan tidak dapat diganggu gugat.
.
selamat bermain.

text:
the time i didn‚Äôt like my own company...
.
.
a mentor of mine challenged me to sit alone in silence with my thoughts for like two whole hours...üôÅüò¶. i don‚Äôt know about y‚Äôall but i can barely be alone with myself for like 5 minutes.  my day is a flurry of hustles...working, writing, creating, parenting, adulting, etc.  i don‚Äôt have time for silence and solitude especially with someone as crazy as myselfü§∑üèΩ‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è. but i did it this a.m. and maybe i learned a couple things.
.
. 
the first is that i hated it...the second is that i needed it.  i hated sitting with myself as my thoughts and feelings amplified and took me to places i didn‚Äôt wanna go. i hated as i stewed over problems, fears, insecurities, and doubts.  i hated having to admit that i‚Äôve been dependent and needy for the company of others.  and i hated having to admit that i liked distraction because it kept me from dealing with my own issues.
.
.
sometimes the only company you need is yourself.  sometimes the only distraction you need are your very own crazy thoughts and feelings üò≥. and sometimes the things we hate to do are the very things we need to do the most.  for me life and creating music are the same...as i grow the music growsüéº‚úçüèæ. i may not be good at sitting alone with myself but i think as i learn to love me more...who knows ü§∑üèΩ‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è...maybe i‚Äôll grow to the like it...even if it means i have to keep company with someone as crazy as myself. üòâüíú #loveyourself
.
.

text:
repeat after me!
no woman of any
age, colour, character 
ever deserves to 
be sexually violated 
of what some might 
lightly call ‚Äúeve-teased‚Äù 
#ineveraskforit 
this is what is written in the card this akeli, awaara, azad girl is holding. since the day i have seen this t-shirt i have been wanting one, it is like it defines what i am. and i am proud of the fact. in this day and time when we are asked to be careful, coy and constrained in what we do. i really feel alone, independent and awara (is there even an english word for awara, i know rouge & loafer could come close but they don‚Äôt quite cut it do they?) is the what we all should aspire to be. to break those barriers society is put around us. 
i have been working with blank noise when they were a tiny little group and it‚Äôs amazing to see what @jasmeenpatheja has achieved over years in this area. @blanknoiseactionheroes are now everywhere and in each one of us when we raise our voice against harassment. come join the fight and become an #actionhero today. be the #akeliawaaraazaad girl, be on your own, be unapologetic, be free! 
#sinamon #womenpower #blanknoise #metoo #metoomovement #claimingit #claimingmyspace #feminist #feminism

text:
@ylex @nyt.fi @nytimes i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still, today, right now.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the fake content - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking a real responsibility.

text:
everyday we go out into the world and make hundreds of choices in thousands of minutes...
left, right, stop, go, good, bad, mean this, say that and many of them are inconsequential, what about the ones that aren‚Äôt?
years ago, someone made a choice that turned into a decision for me; it became a life i didn‚Äôt know.

the choice that has since stolen my peace and quiet, a lifetime of sleep, any strength or resolve i had, and after so many years, burdened my soul with connection to theirs; they ruined my life, without even a passing thought. 
and they had the audacity to lie and beg the world for their life, their future. 
maybe this hurt more. 
choices are actions or words spoken into this world  that normally reflect our greatest desires and longings....it‚Äôs why we don‚Äôt always grasp the other side, we choose us. we make decisions for other people without even realizing it. 
along time ago, someone made a choice to break me and that decision did, the joy, trust, security, pride, confidence, and love i felt in my soul disappeared in an instant. 
and i would say i let them but i didn‚Äôt, i couldn‚Äôt stop them and nothing will ever change that; this was their choice, and now my fate. 
it almost killed me, it tried like hell, and i would never say i‚Äôm a fighter, i‚Äôm not but i am a survivor. 
my mind gave up on me, it couldn‚Äôt stand the despair but my body continued. 
that girl has now become a woman who knows the sad truths and that anything can happen, no matter what we think or do to stop it.
i have endured 8 yrs of torment and the last few years, it has eased into a nagging bitterness and sadness. 
time does not heal all wounds, this will forever trickle blood.
for long, it poured blood; there was no stop.
it drowned my loved ones in anger, fear, and self-hatred.

but i want you to remember that you can do hard things. the world will only break you if you allow it. 
there are so many who love you and while you need to be at 5%, they will be at 100%-i know this and the truth, there are not enough moments in my life to forget what happened. 
you cannot control others words or actions but you decide the moments after, you can do hard things, the impossible.

in the 1880s, the tsar alexander iii decided to build a railway connecting moscow with the far east. after deciding to reject international partnerships, the tsar made the railroad an exclusive russian project with no international partnerships. construction commenced at both ends of the trail. in 1891, his son, the soon-to-be-tsar nicholas ii, laid the cornerstone of the railway station in vladivostok on the far east coast of the country.‚†Ä
‚†Ä

text:
how amazing technology has become in changing fashion for the better. soda company schweppes joined advertising agency ogilvy in creating a high-tech garment. the dress has heat sensors which detect, and record, the areas in which the women wearing them were groped at the club.
.
.
.
this dress is a fabulous invention to help raise awareness of sexual harassment against women. it gives people scientific evidence that yes, this is a problem, and that we should believe people more when they come out against being harassed. .
.
.

text:
i was 18. i had gone to a club with my friends.  we were having a good time, everything seemed perfect and then i met him. he approached me in the smoking area and asked me on a date. i was reluctant at first, but agreed to speak to him for a while before going out.  after 2 weeks, i finally agreed to go out for drinks. i was having so much fun, he was nice, generous and seemed really interested in me. as we were walking to another pub, he asked to kiss me, i agreed. another few drinks, it's getting late, he lives an hour away from me. 
2 am, no trains or buses go back to his, i need to sleep, i have lectures the next day. 
after a lot of hesitation i invite him to sleep at mine with the promise that nothing will happen. he smiles and thanks me profusely. we get home, he throws me on the bed and starts touching me, i push him off and say no. he continues, i say let's go for a cigarette. he agrees. once out of my room, i make him promise that it won't happen again, he says sorry. we go to bed, i turn to my side and say goodnight, trying to stay as far from him as possible. i thought it was going to be ok, then i feel his hand down by back as he tries to pull me towards him. 
i freeze, i panic, now he's kissing me and touching me. 
i say i'm on my period,but he doesn't stop, i tell him "no" over and over, he doesn't stop. out of energy, i zone out and let him do what he wanted.

when i woke up in the morning to my naked body next to his i felt shame, disgust, regret. 
it took me over 4 months to admit to myself what had happened. i thought i could have prevented something like this from happening to me. i was wrong. it doesn't matter how strong you are, how careful you are, these things can happen to anybody. even though i finally came to terms with it, there is a part of me that will never be the same. i hate how he took so much out of me, but this , in a very twisted way,made me stronger.
i don't want to hear countless more stories, it's time to act, time to change the society we live in, we need to end rape culture, i'm done with it being normalised.
#metoo #speakoutweek #endrapeculture
name: #metoo Support Society GS

text: how many times have you sent your child off in the grocery store to grab something? how many times have you seen someone else's child wandering down an aisle alone or meandering through the mall unsupervised? granted, 90% of children know their abuser, there are still opportunistic predators out there who are looking for easy prey. and, because there are no distinctive characteristics about them that scream child molester, they can move in plain site and we are none the wiser until they strike. it only takes minutes for a child to be sexually assaulted, which means sending them over to aisle 7 or letting them run over to the game store while you check out in your favorite store can be just enough time for a predator to attack. remember, people of all races, religion, and socio economic backgrounds molest, so you can't presume to have any inherent level of safety anywhere. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

text:
something big just happened in my life and i need to share. nearly five years after reporting a sexual assault that happened to me while i was attending truman state university and having an incredibly heartbreaking outcome with no closure, today i finally got some justice.
.
my assailant will now be charged with a felony. he was a moroccan exchange student, so he's likely back in morocco, and if he ever attempts to return to the us, he will not be allowed into the country. however, if he is currently in the us, getting pulled over for any reason means he will be arrested and the kirksville police department will come to collect him wherever he may be.
.
the full story is in the link in my bio (content/trigger warning). i've decided to be vulnerable to give a bit of catharsis to as many survivors as i can. i hope you will share this with a sexual assault survivor who needs it. i also have some choice words for truman state, kirksville pd & prosecutors, and everyone who believes most accusers are liars.
-
#sexualassault #metoo #timesup #justiceisserved #feminist #sexualassaultsurvivor #rapeculture #bossbabe #bravery #lifestlye #influencer #stlouis #trumanstateuniversity #truman #kirksville #missouri

text:
@ariannahuff @huffpost this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
working on a new film project for the first time in a couple of years and it feels so good to flex that muscle again. ‚Äúpushed‚Äù is a dance film that examines the relationship between gender performance, violence, the politics of the #metoo movement, using ana mendieta‚Äôs conception of the body as its starting (and ending) point. transcending performance, video, and photo, and spanning more than ten years, mendieta‚Äôs silhuetas series comprises of roughly 200 works in which mendieta‚Äôs form is pictured, or implied, in natural landscapes. this ranges from her body covered in flowers in a pasture, to its shape rendered dramatically in flames, to its outline in the sand.¬†¬†in mendieta‚Äôs work, her body is the subject and object, reframing the position that female subjects, or ‚Äúmuses,‚Äù have taken in the art historical canon, which has seen the female body used, fetishized, and experimented upon under the gaze of white male artists, often known for their poor treatment of women both in and out of the studio (e.x. picasso, matisse, gaugin). the use of self as subject by female artists and imagemakers asserts self-possession and mastery over one‚Äôs body, as well as an instance upon its politics, and a desire to both acknowledge and transgress them. the need for catharsis through art-making becomes an intensely physical act, in which reconciliation and self-possession happen through an insistence upon the body and its occupation of space. gloria lape√±a gallego describes ana mendieta‚Äôs artistic process
as ‚Äúa therapeutic need to mitigate the inevitable wounds of the female artist.‚Äù as fellow feminist artist louise bourgeois might say, art here operates as ‚Äúa defense against anxiety‚Äù and as a project for personal actualisation and resistance. mendieta‚Äôs continued irreverence transgresses normative understandings of the body as static and passive to the artist‚Äôs gaze; as subject and producer, her works feel activated by the energy that she brings to them, as the process of placing her body in unexpected spaces defies not only artistic precedent, but furthermore, the limitations imposed upon her body with respect to race and gender.

excited to be sharing this project soon.

text:
research by fawcett society, a leading gender equality organization, reveals that the #metoo movement has caused a ‚Äúsignificant shift in attitudes to sexual harassment.‚Äù the largest shift in attitudes occurred among people ages 18 to 24.¬†half of them also believe that our societal standards about ‚Äúwhat is acceptable‚Äù are shifting.
some see this change in attitudes as a welcome sign of progress for our culture. but there are also losers in this scenario ‚Äî namely, falsely accused young men. the attitudes about assault are becoming so rigid that the mere leveling of the accusation is enough to severely damage or destroy the lives of the accused, without proving guilt. nowhere, perhaps, is this more pronounced than on college campuses, where the obama administration made a test case of new rules governing sexual engagement pursuant to title ix ‚Äî greatly expanding the scope of a law originally intended to assure gender equality in college sports. #awtalks

text:
you know that old-time christmas classic song, "baby, it's cold outside"? it has been banned by a radio station in cleveland and now other stations are following suit as it's "too offensive to play on the radio". i don't know about you but i loved that song! it was a regular on my christmas playlist :( but i'd never really 'heard' the words until this morning when i looked the lyrics up (i'm obviously a super visual person). yikes. basically, the guy will not take "no" for an answer. there is some back and forth banter, she's gotta go, he's trying to convince her to stay for the night. 
at one point in the song, she evens asks "what's in this drink?"!. um, date-rape much?
there's been some backlash about the ban. where do we stop? we'd have to analyze so. many. songs. - blurred lines, santa baby, it's so easy - 
what are your thoughts? #babyitscoldoutside #ban #metoo#daterape #wdok #cleveland #ohio #radioban #christmassongs#holidayclassic #theanswerisno #nomeansno

text:
12/05/18;
i have this big empty house to myself,
yet i've only slept alone in it a few times.
every noise triggers something inside me,
a slight fear that he is near.
i can still feel his soft skin against mine,
the liquor on his breath across my neck,
his shaking hand around my throat,
his cold fingers down my body,
his slurred words telling me to stop crying.
that he loves me.
that he's sorry.
that i'm his- only his.
i stay awake on the nights when i'm alone,
until i physically pass out from exhaustion.
most days, i beg friends to sleep over, just so i can feel safe enough to sleep.
my family,
my friends,
they know what he did to me,
but they will never understand.
not the way i feel physically,
mentally,
emotionally.
i can still hear his voice telling me he loves me,
after yelling at me for something i said or did.
i feel his painful hips pushing into me,
as i lay limp and cold in my childhood bed.
i still smell the cinnamon whiskey and blueberry beer on his lips,
while he would tell me "you know you want daddy".
i can still picture him throwing up all over himself and crying and begging me to love him again.
but most of all, i can still taste the words he would always say,
again and again,
"you're mine, got it?"
as i lay there,
crying,
begging him to stop.
he tore me open,
limb from limb.
stitch after stitch.
broken shard by broken shard.
i can eventually forgive him,
because i know he is broken too,
but how do i forgive myself?
